  "prompt": "What is the relation between phase and line voltage?",
  "response": "In three-phase electrical systems, the relationship between **phase voltage** and **line voltage** (also known as **line-to-line voltage**) depends on the configuration of the system, specifically whether it is a **star (Y) connection** or a **delta (\u0394) connection**.\n\n### 1. **Star (Y) Connection:**\n- In a star connection, the line voltage (\\( V_{L} \\)) is related to the phase voltage (\\( V_{P} \\)) by the following formula:\n  \\[\n  V_{L} = \\sqrt{3} \\, V_{P}\n  \\]\n  - Here, \\( \\sqrt{3} \\) is the factor that comes from the geometry of the three-phase system.\n  - The line voltage is higher than the phase voltage by a factor of \\( \\sqrt{3} \\) (approximately 1.732).\n\n### 2. **Delta (\u0394) Connection:**\n- In a delta connection, the line voltage (\\( V_{L} \\)) is equal to the phase voltage (\\( V_{P} \\)):\n  \\[\n  V_{L} = V_{P}\n  \\]\n  - This is because in a delta configuration, each line is directly connected to two phases, so the line voltage is the same as the phase voltage.\n\n### Summary:\n| Connection Type | Relationship Between \\( V_{L} \\) and \\( V_{P} \\) |\n|------------------|--------------------------------------------------|\n| Star (Y)         | \\( V_{L} = \\sqrt{3} \\, V_{P} \\)                 |\n| Delta (\u0394)        | \\( V_{L} = V_{P} \\)                             |\n\nThis relationship is fundamental in understanding and designing three-phase electrical systems.",
